Certainty.Level: 8) Unique species-specific modifications in special cases
Modification: Fossils are known from both North and South Africa but the South African fossils appear older than late Pleistocene.  Fossils are known from several sites in Northern Africa listed in Cenozoic Mammals of Africa (edited by Lars Werdelin and Silliam Joseph Sanders). These sites generally do not include multiple species and based on a site in Sudan discussed in (Fossils from Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology Volume 292, Issues 1-2, 1 June 2010, Pages 12-34.) The range should be all of Africa but the fossil range fits better with the range of Gazella sp. and the range is therefore set as the African range of the genus Gazella.
Motivation: Unique species-specific modifications in special cases.

1) Range reductions for species with recent, human-induced range expansions
Modification: Delete the part of the range inhabited by  Eudorcas rufifrons tillonura.
Motivation: The provenance of the type specimens of Eudorcas rufina is unknown and the species have not been seen since. The closest relative of Eudorcas rufina is likely Eudorcas rufifrons and we chose to map the distribution of this species as the distribution of Eudorcas rufifrons tillonura.  Eudorcas rufifrons tillonura is sometimes treated as its own species (e.g. in Mammals of Africa) and since Eudorcas rufina appear distinct from Eudorcas rufifrons rufifrons we interpret it as a synonym of Eudorcas rufifrons tiliana.

Certainty.Level: 8) Unique species-specific modifications in special cases
Modification: The provenance of the type specimens of Eudorcas rufina is unknown and the species have not been seen since. The closest relative of Eudorcas rufina is likely Eudorcas rufifrons and we chose to map the distribution of this species as the distribution of Eudorcas rufifrons tillonura.  Eudorcas rufifrons tillonura is sometimes treated as its own species (e.g. in Mammals of Africa) and since Eudorcas rufina appear distinct from Eudorcas rufifrons rufifrons we interpret it as a synonym of Eudorcas rufifrons tiliana and therefore assign the mapped range of Eudorcas rufifrons tillonura to Eudorcas rufina.
Motivation: Unique species-specific modifications in special cases.

Wildlife Conservation Society, New York. Range expanded to most of the suitable areas in Eurasia but not to the central Arabian Desert and areas of northern Eurasia with average yearly temperatures below 0 degrees. Range expanded to suitable areas on Great Britain.
Motivation: Expansion of ranges for species with known, or at least highly suspected, range declines to cover suitable areas contiguous with the current range.

Certainty.Level: 6) Estimation of ranges based on the natural ranges of the extant species that the target species co-occurred with at fossil sites
Modification: Disjunct ranges connected. No overlap in range allowed with Panthera atrox or Panthera leo.  Range expanded to an apparent gap in eastern Siberia and north the  coast in North America. These areas were outside the estimated convex hull as they are colder than the predicted range based on co-occurrences but the areas contain species such as Canis lupus, Gulo gulo and Vulpes vulpes which are not expected to be more cold adapted than this one.
Motivation: Estimation of ranges based on the natural ranges of the extant species that the target species co-occurred with at fossil sites.
